A Republican strategy to oppose Obama’s re-election
Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center believes the latter to be a myth by reaffirming that election fraud in the U.S. is less common than the number of people killed by lightning strikes.
Republican lawyers have reported only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the U.S. in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for conducting elections in individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of U.S. governments have promulgated new laws that make the procedure for registration or polling more difficult.
This phenomenon has gained importance since the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which there is a judicial act.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states forcing voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identification card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible individuals, do not possess a photo ID issued by a government agency of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a card.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to obtain the required ID.
Young people, minorities and low-income people are disproportionately affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are seen as voters who increasingly vote for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who choose more strongly for the Republican side to use the election cards issued by these clubs.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voices.
It is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in eight states in 2011 supported laws that abolished voter registration on election day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to assist voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaigns to register voters in the 2004 general elections helped to register about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the share of new voter registration by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the time period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although they made up only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same is true of the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, who represented 76% of the voters, accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters have vehemently opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws that require the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
Democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the laws passed and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the states that will decide for 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required in the Electoral Commission to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new rules will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
