Analyzing the Higgs Boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has sparked some excitement last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model - our best or "least wrong" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but empirically has not yet been observed.
But for physicists, it is not yet entirely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still no data to be absolutely certain about it.
Nevertheless, let’s assume that this is actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let’s look at what it’s all about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that makes it impossible for two objects to be in the same place at the same time.
It’s not possible to break this rule – and don’t try too hard because you’ll hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli Exclusion Principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state", with this "state" consisting in large part of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and kindly obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons are moving, an evil band of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can in fact be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which by the way is absolutely amazing) these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not treat here, and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of exceptional banality: the photon or the "particle of light", which is the "boat" of electromagnetic force.
That is, when a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly in this place, in about like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "interference" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable Field
The same is true for the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" in order for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, somewhat comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be crushed by a very large rock.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like CERN is needed – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! – to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator on its own.
And similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do possess a mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) do not possess a mass.
What can all this research be "good" for now, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they serve to review the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to accurately investigate all deviations between the observations and predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who most hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major flaws, since it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (ups!).
However, no such deviations have been found at CERN so far.
Consequences
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be none.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first permanent laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was more of a "laboratory plaything" at first.
You can imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves as an “eye” for all digital cameras worldwide and won it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that you can never really know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With its Committee on Dying in Dignity, Quebec recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate must resume shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the palliative care home Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a tasty lunch, he resignedly agrees to let himself be helped to eat.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is for you to cure my diarrhea because it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees while standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to the childhood stage is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the person's ability to take a step back," he notes.
Because, according to several people working in palliative care, major events are taking place amidst these setbacks.
The patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed by the doctors and nurses who take care of them with so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But through the disease, I really got to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I don’t have any desires in life anymore,” she says, before accepting that a mask is put on to help her breathe.
In the coming days, she is still waiting for the last visit of her son, who is from Italy.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers provide physical care and assistance with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more enjoyable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 people.
That's very little, considering that one day we'll all die.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given an oral care with brandy or pepsi.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died overnight.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help relatives and patients alike,” says Nathalie Savard, the care director.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois there is no day like the other.
In addition to a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family reunion in the yard and is well supported by his pillows as he is honored, a 36-year-old young man, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, tragically dies after trying everything to survive.
“For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois’ home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, either at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Greater Montreal Area, are more or less exclusively specialized in caring for cancer patients.
It is precisely this large inadequacy in Quebec’s health care that causes several palliative care specialists to worry about the passing of a law regulating assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliative care personalities such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to switch to death aid.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without any measures taken to relieve her.
I am afraid that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients bitterly until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard’s chances of survival were minimal when she discontinued severe chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she replied that she regretted that I gave up the fight, she said.
However, she told me that I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the caregiver for not fulfilling this wish after their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Society of Home Palliative Care of the Greater Montreal Area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to the terminal sedation, which results in the patient falling asleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to put me to sleep,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
