A Constitution with the Crusher Rod in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains divided more than ever in terms of the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power of attorney, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on a provisional, multiple-changed text, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only resulted in an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his “autocratic delirium” by continuing to “break his word” and “walk the law.”
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time forcing the brothers to renounce their plan to explain the text to the Egyptians section by section.
For the president, it’s also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as the protest unfolds across the country.
Following confirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
With this resort to a hasty vote, the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum: “Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney”, the latter supposedly should end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this Constituent Assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals did not respond to the call.
Shortly before the declaration of the Constitution in mid-November, they turned away because they felt they had not been able to put their views into effect.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted in the same way.
To achieve decision-making capacity, 11 people, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed in the time for prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the Constituent Assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention, ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had hoped to replace “the principles” with “the rules”, which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
“Philosophy” is the answer of the liberals, who view this only as a propaganda attack.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place over other articles.
They have particularly in mind Article 220, which grants the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying, as "the people who are asked to take a stand have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see in this the first signs of a theocracy."
The fears of the Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, "that there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers here in particular to the "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide on it."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticised for the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In line with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights associations have demanded.
The latter also share their concerns with regard to the text, which they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The act of blasphemy is maintained, and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for the right to free expression, especially for the press.
Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch stresses that the article no longer refers to the protection of women.
In her opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture under Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of salt
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons for visiting Israel.
Worship in front of the holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding party, walking on the water, breastfeeding the seastorm and fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to His disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries are in Jerusalem.
Believers here commit the path of suffering or crossing of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem is also the holiest place of the Jews - the Wall of Lamentation, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave cards with wishes, which then come true.
Take a trip to the heights
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hideout from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings an airlift to this historic summit.
In the north of the country in 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, which attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can reach it by a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the mountaintop.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are nearly 300 museums in this country.
With only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls from the Dead Sea found in rock caves in the Judean desert are preserved, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is on display.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bathers.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most striking section is the Children’s Memorial, which was built to commemorate the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
At the entrance to the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the children of the Jews and of the countries where they died shall be heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned here.
Doing something for health
Israel’s three most important recreational areas are on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise water has a high salt content and therefore even non-swimmers carry it easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural brine) and healing sludge as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of hardened nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets are hidden in the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city passed the famous sea route linking Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to wander through the narrow streets, which are named after signs of the zodiac.
Fortuna is supposed to be the legend according to everyone who touches the walls in the street with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries on photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Today, the carefully restored theatre hosts evening concerts and operas.
List of attractions for tourists
When you drive to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is not taken in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily converted into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed train and in Haifa the only subway line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper city.
To be exact, it is an underground cable car.
A drive within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which is enough including transfers for a drive of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is at rest.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, excluding pork, seafood, peel-free fish and foods that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with hamel and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falabel), as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-nourished cats who roam the streets cozy and unhindered.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
Cats like lively places and don’t say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost on average 30 shekels.
In Numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the United States and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists entered the Promised Land, which is an increase of 51% compared to the comparison period in 2010, before the visa requirement was lifted on February 9, 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While lawmakers and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with counterfeit certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families left in the home.
On 1 December, a law came into force that requires every migrant to take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this scheme only applies to migrants who wish to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in retail.
However, the tests are expected to become mandatory for all guest workers in the future, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
In doing so, you need to pass not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of the legislation.
Language proficiency must be demonstrated both for obtaining and extending the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problems and protection of rights
All of the examinations will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of People's Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centers have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question in the press several times before the law came into force: What does the whole thing actually bring?
What changes does the requirement to demonstrate language proficiency bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, oppose spokesmen of the migration authority, it is about reducing the number of forced workers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," said Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must be protected before you leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical assessment face problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future immigrant without language skills will inevitably meet people with evil intentions, who will put him under the guise of help in a dark, narrow barracks where he will endure dozens of months of his own without food and documents and create 12 to 14 hours a day.
There are a lot of complaints from our immigrants.
"In your homeland, you will be promised one thing, and on arrival you will be cheated, your passports will be taken off and you will not receive the promised salary," said Tolib Schwaripov, head of the Tajik Migration Agency.
Don't scold me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to make money in Russia, admit that they are not only unable to speak the language of the target country, but also can hardly express themselves in their own language in writing.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: Only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only immigrants with legal status are required to pass the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Entry prohibited for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic obstacles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, the legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The employees of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and this then results in cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," Umed Huschkadamov told reporters.
"Don't scare the cost of false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be falsified.
Some forged certificates that certify the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Immigration Authority.
The counterfeit papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive these for free: every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than double the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both civil servants and civil rights activists agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that certificates cannot be bought easily.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who pass the test for the first time that they will get time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where no active contact with people is necessary.
Interior Ministry Ignores Illegal Weapons Market
Proportion of legal weapons in crime is extremely low
The Russian Interior Ministry plans to tighten the gun laws for private gun owners.
This is how the authorities react to the recent events: wounded in the shootings at weddings and seven dead in the amok of the Moscow lawyer Dmitri Winogradov.
The police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal has been supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Combating Corruption, Irina Jarovaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter has been published on the Internet, calling on the authorities to refrain from "senseless exacerbations".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal justice officer, Wasilij Lesnikov, to the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes using registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while for the same period, a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not deter criminals from using themselves on the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors, you can find any kind of weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
Weapons can reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts weapons orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez said.
On the second channel come illegal weapons, which are stolen from law enforcement officers by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen from both the police’s weapons chambers and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons warehouses.
At many military camps, there were frequent explosions.
"There is evidence that in some cases it was a firefight to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military official said.
According to Baranez, gun manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that can't withstand international competition and therefore squander their weapons on the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a production of its own, sometimes artisanal, and a mafia that organizes the smuggling," the former military member explains.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was written by the Center for Problem Analysis and Public Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Criminological Literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
According to investigators, the vast majority of illegal weapons come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all weapons on the black market are there because of "responsible people who have managed to deal with weapons in their work," the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% go back to thefts in weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun shop, who doesn’t want to be named, assures that weapons found at illegal excavations have long since been bought outdated.
According to him, it is more common for dealers to get supplies in a weapons warehouse.
A weapon, for example a TT-type pistol, is purchased via a flag line.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police are, of course, aware of everything and therefore, if they cannot comply with the plan to detect crimes, they periodically conduct control purchases from dealers who offer illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
"Like in a luxury store"
Buyers and sellers most often find out about acquaintances with each other.
I had been looking at websites and blogs when someone became aware of me and suggested that I come to the station "Begowaja" where a person would be waiting for me, who would take me to a certain place where we could then negotiate the price.
