U.S. Fast Food and Supermarket Employees Strike
One in four U.S. teenagers sits behind the checkout desk at Mc Donald's
In recent days, there have been massive protests across the U.S. against low wages in Walmart stores and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as Mc Donald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can yet predict whether the protests will swell further or whether they will soon be out of the air again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing charities.
In addition to raising the modest wages of simple Walmart and fast food employees, the organizers of the protests are pursuing the goal of founding unions.
So far, this sector of the economy is hardly unionized.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called Black Friday, on which sales took place in the U.S., which attracted millions of customers, sometimes leading to hand sweeps.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, put down their work and, together with unions and left-wing activists, enlisted branches of the chain whose target group is low- and middle-income individuals.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in Walmart stores are, on average, between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many of the low-paid Walmart employees only shop at their own workplace.
The prices and product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can often sell the goods only because employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, for example missing forklifts or hand scanners.
Participants in the protests on "Black Friday" called for wage increases and expressed their anger that the contribution to the company's own health insurance had risen from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee who earns $9.5 an hour could not afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from the University of California at Berkeley prove that if the company raises the average salary to $12 per hour, it would cost Walmart $3.2 billion.
That’s about 1.1% more than they currently donate for wages.
If Walmart were to completely reverse the pay increases on customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
For them, that would be a yearly increase of only $12.39 compared to today’s spending.
Proponents of Walmart are pleased to note that there were protests in only nine states, and these did not inflict any losses on the company.
Black Friday lasted in its store from 8 a.m. on Thursday through midnight the next day, and during that period Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, Walmart cashiers performed nearly 100 million transactions on “Black Friday”.
The company’s spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the Huffington Post’s left-wing website that a total of “less than five” Walmart employees quit the job and the protest was just “another PR trick” by the union that organized the protests.
"Free cash!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their target was not Walmart stores (which are undesirable in this progressive city and therefore not existing so far), but McDonald’s and other inexpensive restaurants.
McDonald's says the company sells billions of servings, and yet you are not granted sick days, and you are not paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage is $7.25 per hour under federal and New York law.
In fast-food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually raised, but not too high, and on average, their simple employees in New York get $8.90 an hour.
No one deserves less than her in this expensive city.
How it is possible to get out in New York with so little money is incomprehensible to me.
There was a time when nearly a quarter of all U.S. teenagers were behind the counter after school at McDonald’s, but the teenagers still lived with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw the main source of income or planned to stay there longer.
Now, in interviews with McDonald’s employees, I constantly encounter people who complain that they have to cope with this salary and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment in the forum of the Wall Street Journal, the author of which notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6:30 a.m. on Thursday in front of McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and fast-food chefs receive a minimum wage of $15 per hour, more than doubling the current minimum wage.
They continued to demand the formation of trade unions in the fast food industry.
U.S. law prohibits corporate management from standing in the way of this goal and advising or dismissing union members.
On the other hand, corporate governance does not make it easy for them.
However, the establishment of unions in the fast food industry is also difficult for objective reasons.
The main reason is the high staff fluctuation.
Unsatisfied
There were loud protests that day in front of many other fast-food restaurants in Manhattan.
The highlight of the protests was a meeting at noon in front of McDonald's at Times Square, where some local Democrats spoke, including city councilman Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald's says it sells billions of servings, and yet you're not granted sick days, and you're not going to pay for your work!"
The protesters were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example, mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that "we should work together to support the fast food staff so that they can get a fair wage and achieve the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!"
According to the New York Times, this was the largest action of its kind in the history of the U.S. fast food industry.
However, only a few hundred people were on site, of which by far not all are employed in the fast food industry, where tens of thousands work in New York.
It is not yet clear whether the spark of these protests will mobilize entire masses.
"The brain can only be overwhelmed moderately so far"
The topic of augmented reality, popular among followers of modern technologies, has recently been commonly perceived by the lens of a special glasses.
First, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed a corresponding patent.
However, in a conversation with the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear that the glasses were only a transit station for the company’s scientists.
It encourages the ability to manipulate virtual objects in the air with bare hands and create virtual open spaces.
- Please briefly describe what research your group is conducting.
- We are concerned with the interaction of man and machine, but we want to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity has largely remained stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to anticipate 5-10 years and anticipate the radical changes of this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are progress, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What awaits us in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, much still plays out on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We try to change this by working on real three-dimensional imaging systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We must release the computer world into our physical world and make it more comprehensible.
However, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could complement the real world much easier with virtual objects.
And first of all, we should get rid of this stupid virtual reality helmet!
- What do you think about voice control?
It’s popular, but isn’t it overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform everyone around you about his actions and intentions.
In fact, every kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project where we experimented with short and narrow rather than exhaustive gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gesture and language.
- What do you mean?
- For example, would you ask me to give you this spray can?
They say it and at the same time point to it.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to tell.
- Does this mean that you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and cannot do at the time?
- Not necessarily, but this is a mutual approximation.
I think that in the near future, we will have to work in particular on the development of new sensor types that will allow us to more accurately capture people’s reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they offer a good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- What demands do you make on modern cameras based on your work with Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or anything else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
In this way, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
It is necessary to take into account not only the resolution along the X and Y, but also along the Z axis.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
The human movements are extremely dynamic and, frankly, the current 30 fps are not enough, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our laboratory in Redmond with a adjustable processing delay of between 1 to 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction of man and machine.
For my work I needed exactly the same device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras might solve the problem...
Or aggravate the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera inclinations to see how that helps us determine a three-dimensional position.
If I remember correctly, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that in terms of applying the technology of augmented reality in everyday life, the glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in your hand on the go, but I think the best option would be a "changing" augmented reality in which we could switch from a cloud of glasses to the smartphone,
The glasses are a personal gadget and in it lies their strength (privates can only see you), but at the same time also their weakness, because an augmented reality using glasses prevents you from working with others on virtual objects.
“Let’s imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark of Iron Man, but also to ordinary mortals.
There is one problem that critics often point out: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands feel nothing at all.
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
In my lectures, I often speak of the fact that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could quite well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection document.
She perceives pressure excellently!
But there are also technologies that are actually geared towards giving the “images in the air” something handy, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound rays at a certain point where the finger is located, a feeling that is currently but still as weak as someone breathing over the wrists.
There are also bands for the wrist that affect the nerve endings in the fingers, too, which is a potential direction.
- Did you try to fool the brain?
Let it think that it feels what it should feel when it just sees something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried it yet.
Here lies another task with which we will have to struggle for a long time, namely to let a person who is physically in an enclosed space believe that he is instead in an open, virtually infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), large movable platforms.
So far, the brain can only be overwhelmed moderately, and we still have many hard-working years ahead of us.
That’s what makes work in the field of virtual reality so appealing to a researcher: We are only beginning with many topics.
