Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with a killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth-inhabitants on board are on a quest to find a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question arises, how can we breed in weightlessness or on the replacement planet?
In my opinion, there are not many choices.
De facto, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"These are Mars and Venus," says Wladimir Surdin, a research fellow at the Astronomical Sternberg Institute.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first addressed the issue of reproduction in space in terms of flora.
Half a century ago, experiments with plants were already carried out.
The fourth generation of peas grown in orbit did not differ in the slightest from the earthly species.
It was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, guard eggs were sent into space to explore how weightlessness affects the development of embryos.
It develops a very normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
“The problem is that the chick needs to find a hold; it needs to be able to stand on its legs and start moving,” explains Vladimir Sychev, laboratory director of the RAN Institute for Medical and Biological Problems.
Without a solid base, the chicks overlapped wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely blurred.
The chicks did not respond to light and noise.
Four days later, they simply died.
"Twice we let chicks slip and then we stopped the whole thing because it's simply impossible to work with them there," says Vladimir Sychev about the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be found on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that had already been fertilized sent to space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to continue," says Vladimir Sychev.
After the landing, the space rats got offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not been solved so far.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn from their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, humans can do this in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can generate a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
Women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was with Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our moose flew away, and no one on earth could have answered the following question: Will it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered this question," said space veteran Waithang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Terechkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andrijan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Swetlana Savizkaja, who was in orbit twice and even performed work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there remains a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts, where after long flights everything went well and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even when flying into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valeri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
Yet humanity must find new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the generation of artificial gravity.
The Hydrolaboratory in the Cosmonaut Preparation Center is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here, in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
Water is the weightlessness.
Although adults feel that water is pleasant, it is a foreign environment; however, infants feel that water is a natural element.
It’s as if the little Ichtyanders testify that life on land went out of the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is about 9 months in the mother’s womb in the amniotic fluid, and the fact that it can then become more easily accustomed to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth to the first swim just 2 weeks pass.
"This is too little time to forget something," says baby swimming teacher Marina Aksenova.
While for a newborn child gravity is a much more natural state, the woman does not go without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles form enormously quickly, and thus the ability to push the child out also decreases.
All right, let's get around the birth aid.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valeri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the earth’s attraction, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put in a loading suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply lack what is essential to his life.
“This experiment, which we are doing together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will cause us to give birth to a disabled person, a completely inappropriate person,” says Igor Pestow, head of the Bioethics Commission of the RAN Institute for Medical-Biological Problems.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
Eventually, however, it becomes a reality when the Earthlings in their spaceships depart for a distant planet that will become the home for their offspring born in space.
