Otherwise, they would have nothing to do with our agency, would they?
As for the Czech legislation, what was the significance for your authority of the modernization of the procurement law, do you already feel any impact?
Given that this novella is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had an effect on our tests.
Since our checks take place afterwards, a certain delay must be expected here.
So far, we are more likely to have an impact in the preparatory phase of future controls - so we have introduced the new control instrument "Detection of risks of uneconomicity" and with this almost 14,000 public contracts are examined and analyzed - here the changes will of course have an effect, as the thresholds have been changed, the conditions for certain types of contracts have been changed.
Do you see the passage of this law more positively, or is the system burdened with more bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be complied with.
Already under the previous rules, those subject to an audit are liable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) in the sense that any non-compliance with the award law amounts to a violation of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I do not think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have committed a form error that does not affect actual decision making.
Such a system merely puts bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
Let’s start by saying which path is not the right one.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not illuminate the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what does that mean exactly?
Is the black system now banned or allowed?
After all, a law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then the Prime Minister cannot simply come, and the Office of Control, whose duty it is now to control compliance with the law, can hinder its activity.
He can say, “We change the law and allow the thing,” but he can’t say that we act as if there were nothing.
The procurement law contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and this is also true for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely due to form errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I believe is lacking.
