And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things that we hang in the back...
However, it should also be noted that an improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use the toilets, etc.
However, it is not very common for a larger group of people with disabilities to be actively involved in social events, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when significant athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really begin to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years: What motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a caregiver at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intense.
