Poland and Space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency (ESA) at a Council of Ministers meeting, making it the second member of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish cosmonauts were engaged in space travel, but they did not always come across this as a matter of understanding.
I recall here, for example, the lecture of A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented ideas from his pioneering work "The entrance to cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, which was donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for "Entry to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important proponent of astronomy and space.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's world-renowned contribution to the development of space was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the Earth-facing side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railroad draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or to brake the draisine.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-operated shots.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents handed down, it can be seen that the research has progressed to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric hunting rocket originating from Ing. Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work "Raketa - torpedo azyhna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was terminated from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronauticze) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society was made in the November issue of Problemy magazine in 1954, which devoted four extensive articles to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the creation of an aerospace company.
At the time, there were already the first satellite engineering projects, and it was anticipated that space exploration would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish space company PTA sought to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a regular member in the fall of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 flight tests began in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>dów Desert with the two-stage missile RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed approximately 11.5 kg.
A further stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for observing high winds.
However, in 1962 the further development was stopped.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
From this rocket three types were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport compartment with 0.4 litres of capacity, Meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight altitude for all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland’s accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed two years later by the creation of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second Interkosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
The repeal of the Law on Non-Profit Work is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Law on Non-Profit Works.
This decision sparked a lively debate in the public eye.
It is certainly interesting to look at the issue from a broader perspective.
The liberal economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in a permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of labor (wages), there are price tensions.
This term refers to a situation in which the producer attempts to compete by importing favourable goods by "undercutting" competition in order to obtain a greater market share and increase its profits.
On a large scale, this means for most companies to move their production abroad or to buy cheaply there, or to give up their business, resulting in high unemployment in countries with comparatively high labour costs.
Since private capital does not bear any social responsibility and hence no responsibility for the unemployment it causes, government spending necessarily increases.
This situation is exacerbated by the gentlemen's unwillingness to pay their taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damages they have caused to society as a whole.
This situation is generally known, so concrete statistics are superfluous at this point.
The reckless practice of private capital creates a situation in the individual economies where governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments hand over their own people to private capital, regardless of the social consequences.
This is reflected in particular in amendments to existing laws.
The aim of these measures is to force its own people to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in the wage sector.
This is done, on the one hand, by economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, and, on the other hand, by the circumcision of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as increasing differences between the rich and the poor.
For several years now, there have been public food donations for the poor in Germany who are no longer able to feed themselves by their own labor.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regular cases where workers receive such a low salary that the state must raise their income to the minimum standard of living.
Such a scandal has also been uncovered in the case of auxiliary personnel employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all EU southern states will undoubtedly end up in the same state in which people are forced to emigrate under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of their social level (as was the case in the 19th century), or to work for a hunger wage on the margins of society, hoping that private capital will be invested.
Naturally, this raises the question of where this capital comes from.
When it comes from another EU country, only poverty migrates from one country to another; or capital remains the same, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or in Africa at all, workers work for a fraction of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim to the utmost that the state is not allowed to participate with capital in its own economy, and that the planning economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital insists tightly on its position that the state should not intervene in the economy by directing.
But then one must ask whether private capital does not influence or even direct politics and thus the entire state in its own selfish sense.
Here is the clear answer: yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, mutual favoritism, legislation in which virtually everything is punishable but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that, in the absence of finance, a State Ministry commissions private law firms closely intertwined with the industry to draft legislation.
These bills will then be passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer comes from the people, as proclaimed by the Western constitutions, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Apparently the liberal democracies are now quickly falling into a situation, as Appian describes in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic in the days of Caesar and Pompey: "The state has long been in decay, and the offices have been occupied by force.
Against lubrication money, through illegal blurring of advantages or with stone and sword.
Corruption grew indiscriminately, and the people went to the polls with already bought votes" ... "People of character did not apply for offices, so that the state did not have a consul for eight months as a result of this decadence" ... "It was already really started to talk about the fact that the only medicine used in this difficult situation was c...
As it turns out, today’s society, as in antiquity, is based on the reckless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital is already, by its very nature, incapable of recognizing and enforcing the advantage for the whole of society.
The result, today as then, is an unprecedented decadence of elites who are not at all striving for deeper reforms.
The cause of the rise of fascism and communism must therefore be sought in the reckless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From the current state of affairs, the collapse of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause in which the next round is already taking place.
Especially catastrophic is the fact that today’s elites face the possible loss of hundreds of thousands of human lives in the future, the humanitarian and social disasters we are already witnessing today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from older and newer history, in complete ignorance.
The repeal of the law on non-profit works is not a solution here, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to push the social level of the population down.
This trend is therefore system-related.
The only solution is targeted political-social reforms that increase the state’s capital participation in the economy, increase the citizens’ influence on the government, and weaken the monopoly of private capital in society in favor of the state.
