The Movie Argo: When the Worst Is Calling Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they called for the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had maintained patronage over his regime for decades.
For the US government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, she was unable to enforce the release of the hostages.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to free the hostages only made things worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages at home evoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover up their true identity – they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film crew who allegedly visited the country’s filming locations for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan, developed by "Exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialist magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Hussar piece such as the movie Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels in the film vary - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic contemporary photographs, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly spiked therefore.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the official floors, on the phone...
With this film, Ben Affleck has achieved a remarkable restart of his career.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor, he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film not to feature in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feel for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that made the director’s previous films stand out from Hollywood’s standard.
Affleck, however, also demonstrates this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the opening sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story takes place.
Affleck and his team also have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the wrong film staff at a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the film sense.
However, he works quite successfully with the few, sometimes reminiscent of reality - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted from a phone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its over-spreading, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserved more space, and so they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film thus loses some traction, a film that can be followed with a certain interest, while dripping the design and retro style that reminds of a 70s thriller.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that is alive to this day in a certain way and as proof of how overwhelming the ideas of the omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services are.
