"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there's something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician in a nearby large company, says, "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has Internet, iPad and e-books.
No one volunteers to go to one of these old-style libraries today, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town hardly to visit at the gates of Rotterdam, is a remarkable record holder.
The 80,000-population municipality has the lowest educational rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
To counteract this stupid circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes as nicely brushed steel concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to become the master of statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of bold bar charts and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with the usual serenity and appeared at the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury was still staring at itself in dismay and hunched back, the daring Maas piled up his exquisite coin of the size of a pyramid and ended his actionist-backed speech with the words: "Dear City Council!"
So this is my proposal for the Bookberg of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Bookberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain has exploded.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground garage, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and townhouses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, the faceless small town restaurant, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an unfathomable ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to a piece of contemporary architecture richer.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural construction in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression: book dorado under cheese bell.
There is an elevator that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the real pleasures of space and reading open up when climbing the topography on foot.
The glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lights unmistakably speak the language of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
Everywhere books, books, books.
“Normally, the bookshelves are along the facade, and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We have put the classic room configuration on top of the head and tilted the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the library is well used: in the middle are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and home technology center.
A special pleasure are the black book shelves, which are sometimes wall cladding, sometimes armor, sometimes climbing railings.
Optics, haptics and smell are foreign.
Even incarnate architects and civil engineers shake their heads about the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the Spijkenisse Municipality, at the request of the standard.
And so one day, in a Frisian farm, we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture.
For many years, a millimeter-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root base in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one, two seasons, after which it is ripe for the garbage.
For the library, the fleece was pressed - for the first time in these quantities - to four centimeters thick plates.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) discolors into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like a shoe.
After 105 steps, you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-metre hike, you will be rewarded not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and stuffed ficus trees.
They provide an atmosphere, but above all for the right humidity in the literature mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but this house is, despite the many glass surfaces, a flagship project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Bucherberg is under a glass fall, the sun shines only briefly inside even on sunny days.
The wide wooden glue binders, which are transverse to the glass facade, serve as a shade and capture much of the sun’s rays.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic rollers.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also there.
And also TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse’s “long overdue soul”.
The reason: For the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal stock.
For the first time, the optical gaps in the library - currently 70,000 pieces - are to be filled.
The concept has been taken up.
The shelves are filled to the top.
“Nothing is worse than a half-liter library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's only for decoration.
With this, MVRDV has succeeded in that royal discipline, which is called in professional jargon identity foundation.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
No matter how young and unskilled she may be.
This is finally a point of view for identity.
Szabo: "Germans need to play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
What's that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, due to its special relationship with Israel, Germany must now be cautious.
But at the same time, I believe it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence – but without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was eventually enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is currently transforming its foreign policy away from a policy that was managed by the United States, so to speak, towards a German foreign policy.
It is difficult to add that the Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans, therefore, find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still getting closer to their role, but they are on their way to a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy like they have France or Britain.
What does “normal” foreign policy mean in Germany?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are to some extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
First, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it is necessary to be careful not to confront the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That certainly plays a role.
But I wouldn’t want to put too much weight on it either, that’s not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining in important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe and even in the United States there is a great understanding of the German position.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Maybe Germany will even show some respect for it.
Because it signals that it is taken seriously as an international player and its interests must be taken into consideration.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The United States, on the other hand, has vetoed it.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
Due to American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think that under Obama, the government secretly has quite a lot of understanding for the European position.
But due to the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I don’t think the actual differences are as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to agree on its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand, and on the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a bit easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
