Facts about Sexually Transmitted Infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomaviruses, herpes genitals or hepatitis.
Felt lice and ticks belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and Tripper are most common in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five of all syphilis cases reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonas, candidiasis (fungus), trippers and human papillomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The prevalence of HIV is relatively low among heterosexual adults in this country - yet around 20 percent of new HIV infections belong to this group.
Chlamydia infections are much more common in adolescents than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
Human papillomaviruses are also common among adolescents.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are required to be reported.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1,697 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
That’s about a tenth less than the year before.
What symptoms indicate a sexually transmitted disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, problems urinating, discharge, lower abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not offer 100% protection.
In some cases, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through lubricating infections and close contact with the body.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially with frequently changing sex partners.
Early diagnosis can cure most STIs and avoid late consequences.
