"The Revolution is Back"
The opposition has been forming for weeks against the supremacy of the Islamists.
Tens of thousands gathered in unusual controversy on Friday evening in Tahrir Square in Cairo and vowed to overthrow the charter before it could enter into force.
“The revolution is back and we will win,” said Hamdin Sabbahi, third-placed in the presidential election.
Nobel Peace Prize laureate and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El-Baradei said the draft constitution belongs "to the garbage mountain of history".
Through short message service Twitter, he accused supporters of wanting to lead a "putsch against democracy".
"If he calls the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him," opposition leader Jasser Said said.
"We are not yet tired, the blood of our brothers is not yet expiated," Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Chaled Ali as saying.
And several judges announced that they would not want to monitor the referendum, which would invalidate it.
"The Qur'an is our Constitution"
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, in turn, blew up to counter-demonstration, but cautiously not on Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other Nile in front of Cairo University.
Many disguised women and followers of the Salafists took part and shouted, “The people are demanding the application of God’s law.”
They demanded of Mursi, "Clean the land!" and said, "The Qur'an is our constitution."
A struggle for supremacy over the symbolic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would probably have evoked civil war-like conditions.
Mursi’s supporters obviously didn’t want to risk that.
The Muslim Brotherhood said that both the opponents of the draft constitution and the proponents had spoken out loud and clearly.
Now is the time to let the people decide in the ballot box which direction the country should go in.
A majority for the Islamist draft is considered safe.
"The word human rights does not even occur"
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry about this forced constitutional process, which was supposed to go until February and involve all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood while they were in prison under Mubarak or in court.
Not because he would share their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, convicted, imprisoned.
"And now the word human rights is not even in the new constitution," he lamented in conversation with the "World on Sunday".
Mursi's extension of power to all three powers in the state made the lawyer resign.
These measures are flagrant violations of democratic rules of play and will lead Egypt to a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the president is de facto repealing it," Saeda lamented.
But without civil society organizations, democracy cannot work.
Saeda feels alone, also by the international community, which sees the ideological struggle on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
That could be revenge.
A protester on the Tahrir warns: "You are raising a monster that you can no longer control."
Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most odorous fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living – not only in Europe, but all over the world.
Could the country’s secret to success have anything to do with the local appetite for pretty bad-smelling fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, damp sportswear.
And lay them there for a week.
You have to imagine the nose-drenching smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow here, spectacular landscapes - and that stubborn smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is salt-sprayed trout, which is fermented in water for up to a year depending on how stink you would like your fish to be.
When the darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a party here in Fagernes, which is dedicated to this, now, really very specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works in the local fire department, but also hosts the festival as the so-called "Rakfisk-General".
Around us, people eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
"Many people like the aquavit more than the raccoon fish," says Havard.
The spirits can suppress the smell.
I'm going to cost you a few bucks.
If you avoid bringing the raccoon close to the nose, it’s not bad — like sushi, which has a pretty long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a completely different, much poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling options and fish was drunk in airtight saltwater barrels in the autumn.
In the deepest winter, it was then removed after long fermentation and consumed - undoubtedly with the help of alcohol-dampened senses.
A generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labor market, high wages and a comprehensive health care system.
Even from Sweden, the old rival who was far richer than Norway not too long ago, immigrants flow.
Rakfisk is regarded as something important – as an essential, albeit strictly scented, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the most expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs proudly 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t often get into the world press, and most people don’t seem to mind.
Anders Breivik, the racist right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year, is still hated here.
Instead, it refers only to the “July 22 incident”.
Norwegians find it hard to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Since the early 1970s, the growth of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world has been mainly responsible for Norway’s current wealth.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays of ripe rake fish and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and stinging blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a wise people.
Your English is perfect, just like most people here.
We're not very arrogant, we don't like bragging.
Norway has been very cautious with its oil wealth - a large part of the industry's revenue is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the global economic crisis, everyone threw money around them that they did not possess at all, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
“As long as we can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we are happy,” says Anna.
"And, of course, eat rake fish," she adds with carefree laughter.
I stand in the snow and stand for another dish - I've had enough of Rakfisk.
Such an elk burger is definitely something else. The juicy meat mouths me.
But in the evening the stinking fish is again on the menu.
The hotel I’m staying in is one of several venues that organizes a Rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best – or perhaps the most challenging sense of smell – of fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clad showmaster surrounded by plates of Rakfisk.
The show is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard".
They clapped and laughed.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by aquavit.
But maybe it's the harsh fume of the whole fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces a difficult start
As future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office, the BBC’s Will Grant analyzes the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad.
Even on better days, this is an ever-closed city, but on Monday a steel ring was erected that blocks several major traffic routes to the capital and creates chaos on the streets.
The goal, however, was not to disrupt commuters on their way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will hold the presidency and take over the nation’s leadership.
He faces a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, Mexico has proven itself economically well, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My government is strongly committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto said earlier this week in the Oval Office to U.S. President Barack Obama.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before he stepped up with the U.S. president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions are divided about the new head of state.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto built and which represents a great improvement over the fragile, rugged roads that once existed here.
Plaques bearing his name also hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and lasting changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the party Pena Nietos, the PRI.
In particular, with regard to security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so urgently needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations for Enrique Pena Nieto.
The accusations of the opposition, the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has great plans for the country.
He is an excellent politician, but above all, he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was enlisted to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
In the last two years alone, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left on a patch of brachland near a large garbage dump.
During Governor Pena Nieto's tenure, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murder of innocent women.
The critics of Pena Nietos believe that he at least did not adequately address the problem of women’s murders during his term of office.
But in the worst case, his government has closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the downtown area, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her life partner.
"When I arrived at her house, it seemed as if her body had been washed," recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and the stiffness had already been used.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall. It is attached next to a cross that bears one word: justice.
But this is exactly what, according to the family, has been denied to her so far.
The authorities treated me like I was a talker, a troublemaker, a nurse.
They want you to simply accept their verdict and keep your mouth shut.
“But that’s not possible if there were so many form errors and omissions,” she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential bid on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have suffered from violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his tenure.
“I hope as president he is the way he was as governor,” says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of.
Prosecutor's Office Says Bradley Manning Didn't Complain About Abuse
Prosecutor's Office Against Bradley Manning's Allegations of Being Abused in Prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time at the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a rejection of the charge on the grounds of too harsh detention conditions
The U.S. Army Freedman is Accused of Stealing Thousands of Confidential Documents
The U.S. Attorney General’s Office on Friday tried to establish that Army-free Bradley Manning — accused of the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history — failed to file several cases of military abuse.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Major Ashden Fein explained that records of weekly visits that prison officials had made during Manning's nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, showed no complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a defense request to dismiss the charge - Manning had already been punished sufficiently by the harsh term of detention - Manning had stated that he had contemplated suicide in prison.
The U.S. military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his time in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he had been incarcerated under enhanced detention conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officials asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Finn interviewed him on the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged treatment by his guards as "excellent" and treatment by the institution as "very professional" overall.
The forms, so fine, did not contain complaints about abuse, although officials had interviewed Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning responded that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated to deal with them, but that they had not been recorded.
"They wrote (after discussing the concerns) 'No problem', and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during this meeting was to downgrade his observation status to "prevention of injuries".
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status - one level under threat of suicide - to his own and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and get rid of the observational status to prevent injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life in my view," Manning said.
Manning said on Thursday that he was arrested and transferred to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the prison of the Quantico Marine Base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had contemplated suicide in Kuwait and had once become unconscious due to the heat.
Not being allowed to know what is happening to him or in the outside world has been stressful.
"My world shrank on Camp Arafjon, on this cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I'd die in this cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell — at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours — and without company.
They only allowed him a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay on the move because it was forbidden to sleep or even just lie down during the day.
He had always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and the guards could not see his face, they woke him up so that he would turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an accusation he made in his statement on Thursday - he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico for one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had stated that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
During the interview on Friday, Manning said he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should have dropped the blanket with which he could have covered himself, but he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had stated that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, having previously tried to show an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the official he could have used the bandage of his underwear or flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take his detention experience into account and drastically reduce his detention sentence should he be convicted in his trial before the military court, which is set for early next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will plead guilty to minor offences, while other charges that are considered too extreme are to be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend and the Prosecutor’s Office is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon maintains its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the regulations that apply to all detainees detained in Quantico under the highest security measures.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, illegally publishing intelligence information on the Internet, transmitting national defense information, and stealing public property or documents.
If found guilty on all charges, he faces life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis.
Many people have been forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the emigrants – they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport checkpoint when inconvenience spread within me.
Signs pointed to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure which one I should go to.
I grew up in Central California and was called "Mexican" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Ireland" or my friends in New York "Italians".
Later, I chose "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s homeland there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least well enough to assert myself in that language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I don’t get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in the queue for foreigners.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those topics that are expected when the minds of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is a reason why Mexicans today are equally likely to stay in Mexico rather than emigrate to the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto swore to continue Mexico’s war against the drug cartel, even though he did not give any details in this regard.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country’s leadership under guns to leave more than half of its territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. government official makes even the slightest criticism of Mexico, complaints are heard - in the Mexican press and among the country's elites - about how the Americans are oppressing the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma are on the path of war.
And yet, Mexico’s biggest challenge lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. People for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, a person - perhaps a parent or grandparent - was not given a chance in Mexico and emigrated to the north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty is to them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may now be living the American dream, attending good schools and getting good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we are living – not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial to a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In your opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And then we wouldn’t see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain now – with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are – and Mexican Americans take this away from them.
While a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel like they don’t belong to either country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should have learned during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: Some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to re-establish their connections to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as temporary “ambassadors” for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We want to tell our American colleagues how great it is to visit this country and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties to Mexico.
Oh, well.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And in the face of unfair income distribution, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through this alone, friends.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico one and a half centuries ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge for how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to suffocate such hope in the bud.
In the midst of the usual culprits, countless buildings were laid in rubble and ashes, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis were killed – and for the first time, rockets from Gaza near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem were hit.
But even though Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this mess.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly patch situation could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems anything but appropriate given the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 continues, the fighting this week has strengthened the hardliners on both sides.
The leader of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed the Israelis back, even though his group itself has suffered heavy losses.
Although several Hamas leaders have been killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are trapped in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders might come to the conclusion that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a reinvigorating regional power once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken up the Hamas party – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Rejoicing Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist character may be facing the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies are facing the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt – the by far most populous and most important Arab country – on the southern flank of Israel has permanently changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his overthrow in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the brotherhood with Hamas is weakened and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that cannot even be pushed out by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome", has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more peacefully.
In diplomatic terms, the United States remains firmly committed to its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalation of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers - not least thanks to the blockades that run into the West Bank and thus into the main part of a possible Palestinian state.
Netanyahu’s Likud party has joined an even more militant group in the run-up to the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these insidious Palestinians slander and leave them their own state?
If they actually had control over the West Bank, wouldn’t they just fire rockets just like their fellow fighters in the Gaza Strip?
No, it is better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Maybe the hardliners will be able to make it through, but the Arab Spring could make a difference.
Even if the Islamists now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will first focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense is larger than its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to restore their economy.
That pragmatic President Mursi has teamed up with Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire could be a promising sign – and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think longer-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking cumbersome steps towards democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder keg that will undoubtedly one day explode into Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only exacerbate.
Bloody missions to push back Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand their diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside.
The correct answer is one represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: Two states where Israel is ceding territories for security purposes.
The small hope for the near future is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must now halt arms supplies in the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, complemented by territorial exchange and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also encourage Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the forthcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama, too, must contribute to pushing Israel into negotiations.
During his first term in office, he failed to come up with his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems as if he is equally reluctant to participate.
But this is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a significant interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace treaty between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws on uniform cigarette packaging come into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packages that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging laws have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colors with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing what parts of the body are sick and children affected by cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font, is from Saturday onwards.
With this, Australia introduces the world’s strictest regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to remove young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
Studies have shown that people who haven’t started smoking at 26 are 99% more likely to stop smoking afterwards.
"You can already see in young children that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a minor impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favour black market trade, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer much larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, notes that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the intolerable packaging has risen enormously since the British American Tobacco Group, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan's Tobacco Corporation took over their lawsuit two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units of wholesale stores and is awaiting new stocks.
This is a good deal for us.
According to experts, the hook lies in the popularity of social media with exactly the population group to which the plan is aimed.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, banned them from appearing as sports sponsors, and forced most retailers to stop exposing cigarettes in stores. Now the tobacco advertising has switched to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned online advertising by local businesses and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Those who market tobacco and only have a small area left to promote their products don’t get around the internet,” says Becky Freeman, a researcher in health care at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook, Freeman has seen an increase in reviews of brands written by “very normal people.”
You have to ask yourself: Is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that she even makes a video for it – or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says the industry is focusing on dealing with the new laws instead of marketing.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations – those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, even though none of the countries conducts major trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
