In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored once in a while.
This Thanksgiving I spent unexpectedly five hours at the airport when our plane crashed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to get a few thoughts boring.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is pretty annoying – even when books, magazines, and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts are leading boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us—and our children—to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us nowadays are almost constantly staring at one or the other screen, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
Should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
And no.
I'll come back to that again.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has evolved with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) does not see this as such.
“In fact, boredom has a very long history,” he says.
Pompeii’s house walls adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom that dates back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of wanting to perform a satisfactory activity but not being able to do it.
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in a “disturbance of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is only passing slowly.”
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, even if we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in German for example: "The Inactive Mind: The Definition of Boredom under the Aspect of Attention", published in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to a previous experiment involving a magnifying glass.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content, others heard it at low volumes, so it was hardly perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said they felt more boredom than the other two groups—they had trouble concentrating, couldn’t find a reason for it, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at Guelph University in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
If, on the other hand, you practice a monotonous activity - "like looking for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help you not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that apples and crumbs, often interpreted as signs of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to walk around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," Fenske said.
We all get bored at some point – my delayed flight, a loudspeaker, a particularly tiresome film.
But some people get bored easier than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a “boring susceptibility scale” in the 1980s.
On the scale, statements like “Many things I have to do repeat and are monotonous” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have enough time for everything.”
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida—particularly in terms of the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a fairly relaxed bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adults were bored in school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored when they weren’t at school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is sure that "youth is felt to be particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have much influence on their daily routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall prey to gambling or drugs to alleviate them – studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors investigate the relationship between boredom and creativity. This opinion is Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the topic for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
When you are bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you become happy.
However, while television can provide feelings of happiness in the short term, these flee again in the long term.
So if your child is bored with an iPad, he can get rid of the boredom, but he has not learned to talk or control himself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: “Self-control transfers from one situation to another.”
The child not only learns to talk, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we view them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant hustle and bustle of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredom is the tormenting, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that people are really just looking for a way to turn off and relax.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated, it’s hard to get involved once the noise is muted.”
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new Marijuana Act
19-year-old community college student and footballer Anthony Orozco faces trial in southeastern Colorado for a crime that will soon be legal in that state: the possession of fewer marijuana scraps and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
