"We're being treated like criminals," Orozco said.
But is he also one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state’s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for self-use, the response to hundreds of minor drug offenses depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of law and order violations that revolve around marijuana are already being dropped here and in the state of Washington, which approved similar measures.
The police authorities no longer prosecute adults over 21 years for possession to a small extent, which will be allowed by law as soon as the new laws come into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in the more conservative Colorado districts have announced they are continuing to prosecute existing marijuana crimes and are still quoting people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are agreeing to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana businesses from opening in their communities.
“This situation is evolving so rapidly that I don’t even know what’s going to happen next,” says Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
And even regulators in Washington state are scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on the establishment of a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - with a deadline of 1 December 2013 in mind.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado is in any case ahead of most states when it comes to regulating marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for self-consumption.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well suited for orientation," says Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Supervisory Authority for Spirits.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve the purpose of a rough guide.
“We don’t have a real precedent to follow,” he adds.
The Washington law, called I-502, comes into force on December 6 and thus also forms the endpoint of a grey zone in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but ownership is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified during this time - such as how the state's requirement of "reasonable access" to licensed marijuana is to be agreed with the ban on cannabis shops within 300 meters around schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
“Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, particularly the Seattle metropolitan area,” said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his employees in Aurora stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses in people over the age of 21, and that the police would not seek criminal charges for these offenses “from now on.”
Chief Oates added that the police will continue to enforce city regulations to regulate growers of medical marijuana and drug dealers will continue to be prosecuted.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck has a stricter view.
After the vote, he stated that his authority would continue to prosecute cases of marijuana possession, mainly to move consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people are liable for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana in court, although many have also been charged with other crimes.
"Our authority has a duty to prosecute offences that were criminal offences at the time of the crime," Buck said in a statement.
The reactions are dubious even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county’s largest city, no longer show up adults for possession of smaller quantities.
The district attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all pending possession proceedings.
“I don’t think I’m wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes,” he says.
Although 55% of voters in Colorado supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that it would not be easy to reconcile personal marijuana use with the complexities of government and the legal system.
And the contradictory reactions across the state fostered a deep divide among local officials regarding the big green experiment to date.
District attorneys are a “cultural barrier,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents defendants in court for marijuana offences and acts locally as a spokesman for the national organization to reform marijuana laws.
“They’ve spent so much of their lives prosecuting people that they still can’t accept legalization,” he believes.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are treated as national cases for the legalization of drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an era of legal sale, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at federal level as a crime.
Proponents of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will give in.
Despite several eye-catching arrests of consumers and sellers of medical marijuana, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that while criminal officials are unlikely to step in to seize smaller amounts of drugs, they are likely to be reluctant to tolerate legal, state-regulated marijuana deals under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before the election day, some local municipal administrations approved moratoriums on new marijuana businesses, although these could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, passed a six-month ban that is likely to be passed next week.
“We don’t want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community voted against this amendment.
We are judged by what the community has chosen, not by what the state has chosen.
Many questions are still open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I am Tory
Not only university students today are attacked for their views
It has always been my dream to have a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended the university that I once considered the greatest stamp of knowledge in the world, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization – free thought and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my move to Worscester College in the late eighties – where I had planned to study history – I had packed my suitcases again and thus brought about the first scandal of my life.
My father broke into tears.
My friends were confused.
In the Evening Standard, it was said that I had left because I had a problem with comrades having sex in the neighboring room.
Author A. N. Wilson said that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
The truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I did, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my very unusual name, or because I had come from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason – a reason that seemed so narrow and cruel in this alleged cradle of enlightenment: My now deceased father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate rights students is suffering from similar persecution.
The organized and growing hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for the same equal protection that benefits gays, disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Corpus Christi College’s Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are “often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable” because of their political views.
They are demanding a seat on their college’s Equal Rights Committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Her situation was exacerbated by a recently aired documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It featured, among other things, graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Conservative Students' Association at Oxford University, who was driving in a Rolls-Royce and wearing a silver suit and silver-studded walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered "sin goats for introducing higher tuition fees."
20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the University of Nottingham’s Conservative Students’ Association, said in a Sunday newspaper: “There is a growing left-wing trend in universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing us."
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student in Corpus Christi who initiated the request for greater protection, believes such a climate is "unpleasant". 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, designated president of the Conservative Students' Association of Oxford, says she has seen a growing rejection of moderate rights students among JCR members.
“This poses a threat to intellectual discourse and the well-being of members,” she says.
In my first weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to give Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an honorary degree due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have even frightened Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester-week, when new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of the future events.
I experienced that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even took part in it with pleasure.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, the privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime found their way into the wood-painted spaces of the tutorial.
At my first of these events I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English. I had not been caught up in what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled upon it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and pretty ugly.
"Do Thatcher supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students laughed.
There were tears in my eyes.
“I suggest that you take a few hours of French in your spare time – so if you’re not too busy with your social activities,” Pitt grunted.
I returned to my room with my head hanging.
That evening, I was sitting in college alone at dinner when someone gently tapped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the Conservative Student Association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is the way it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is being harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father, Margaret Thatcher, is coming, so it's going to be worse for you.
Most Tory first semesters pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
In a local pub, I later tried to adjust myself.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs. Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and business, who had ironically attended the conservative Eton College, told me, "You're the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverse and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They fight each other, don't they?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to lead a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay before me stretched before my spiritual eye to a purge of disdain and isolation.
The only tutor who openly recognized himself as a Tory was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History, who had his seat in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for them.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for its Marxist-determinist historical perspective.
In 1997 he took a professorship at the University of Bilkent in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began to commute between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said small-mouthedly.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreaming tower peaks.
Even my communist friends have always displayed impeccable manners.
His wet eyes became cloudy.
Give the whole thing a chance.
I'm sure you're just being bullied.
It would break my heart if you went.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also a Tory supporter, had yielded to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week in which another history tutor seriously claimed that I was “an enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Although I secretly shunned, I admitted that my parents had subjected me to a “brainwashing” and called them “old fools.”
The relief lasted only briefly.
It was my father who hit the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my rabbits gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
You'd be happy to call me a tearful cock.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer from such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic, it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
