The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano put their life and health at risk by carrying 70 kilograms of sulfur over the steep, rocky roads.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their lives by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones that can weigh up to 70 kilograms in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the bouncy stone paths.
Although it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2386 meters, the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb at the turtle’s pace, keeping their balance and carefully putting their steps so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
Arrived on top, they pave the way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiresomely heavy baskets three kilometers up to the scale that a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the occurrences in the volcano since 1960 and (never better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for every kilo of sulfur.
This is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 eurocents) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of plywood, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route", explains Anto, who normally makes three trips a day.
For each route it takes three hours, after which it is completely done, but at the end of the day it has 138.000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable wage for such an almost inhuman effort, however, is three times what he would earn from fieldwork.
"The daily wage of miners here, where coffee harvesters are paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the bearer, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6.2) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I converted her to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been putting his life at risk at Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already left its first traces, even though he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'm going to work here for two more years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than just acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent but life-punished young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist at a hotel, but instead he does the work of a porter.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and gets up every morning at two o’clock because the sulfur also emits at night, where its characteristic yellow color glows blue in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
About 400 carriers load the baskets of sulfur onto their shoulders on the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur mining to save costs, and does not provide any equipment to the carriers who work on their own account and are paid for by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) extra per camera, which the guardians of this natural park together with the admission fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) demand from tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrier.
“This work is for animals and not for humans,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old bearer who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
