Conclusion of the UNASUR Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was theoretically to be signed by the seven present rulers.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Session of the heads of state and government of the Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the cloister, but then explained that it would be published at some point on the website of the Peruvian government.
When asked about the text, they said that the contents were presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements.
Journalists’ access to information on the summit was limited at any given time.
During the day, in the press room, only the image of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted with the message "private meeting, limited audio".
The few information circulating among the journalists were received from the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the Peruvian presidential office sent an e-mail to the media with the summit's "final declaration", but it was Humala's declaration and not the official document to conclude the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South American-Arab Summit (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite press urging, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not published.
On the official website of the ASPA, you can be sure that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that information systems were available for journalists, but they severely restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of The Hague that resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would adopt the decision of the IGH, which begins on Monday in The Hague, in the process of initiating the Lima v. Santiago, to listen to the pleaders of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences that we are currently bringing before this international court," Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and remains a country that adheres to international law, seeks peaceful settlements to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to the international courts," Piñera added, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the IGH came after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered a serious mistake, had filed an action against the Bogotá Agreement, agreeing to submit to the judgments of this international court.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasur since the removal of its president Fernando Lugo in 2011, did not participate in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit shortly after lunch in Lima.
The head of state reads the final document, in which it announced that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set over an investment amount of a total of $ 17 billion.
On the decisions taken, he said that the UNSUR countries will take "significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we are extending the decisions on the right of residence."
He said measures would be taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban uncertainty and organised, cross-country crime, as well as measures to improve access to drugs and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters."
With the crisis in Europe, “economic consolidation (in Latin America) should not take triumphant features, but should serve to expand our production performance and show our peoples a better future,” added Humala.
“We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects that aim to improve spatial connectivity in South America and especially in rural and border areas ... thus uniting our countries and opening up new economic forms,” the president said in a readout.
Among these projects were five Peruvians, which are located on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which are intended to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
Similarly, the final document referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country will serve to re-establish it in the Union of South American Nations," he said.
The need for Latin America to continue to be an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting in Mexico on Saturday with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict respectfully after a judgement of the IGH challenged by Bogotá.
