Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The basketball world champion, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, has been associated with basketball for more than 60 years and has traveled the world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a large spiritual collection of the history of the country's basketball as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was a part of this sport for 6 years, whether as a player of lower classes, player of the first national league, proxy and head of the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or President of the Basketball Association.
“My whole life I put on many hats in basketball, even several at the same time, when I was president of the BSN, chief executive of the national team and president of the association in the 90s,” recalled Reyes during a visit from Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
“Basketball was my life.”
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those of his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, when he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-director or managing director of the club.
“These were my best years I’ve enjoyed most because I’ve been part of eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as a CEO, co-CEO or coach.
It was many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to a championship in 1981, the year of Jerome Mincy’s debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" took over Ortiz, who was a very good manager," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), saying to me, “I have a very strong and 2m tall player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended the free throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who became a citizen and was one of our best throwers.
I remember how he said that if Mincy had enabled a championship for Bayamon, Gausse would provide another.
The championship of the Vaqueros with Gausse was awarded to him, but already from a distance, because he was already at the top of the association in 1988.
At that time, he preferred to enjoy his executions and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember the first time we won the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico against the United States.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we were fourth, which would have been Bronze if it had not been for this Canadian referee who had us repeating the last move for the second time, Reyes said.
Was this group of the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as well as those who won the 2004 Olympics against the Dream Team.
But my favorite is the team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered the team of the United States a fight, as when they won bronze against us at the World Cup.
Not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz) were back on the team, but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be on the team because of a knee injury in 1990.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which brought us great joy, was that of the 1995 pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner as substitutes for the blocked players due to the events at the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against every prognosis.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was undoubtedly Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as much as Piculín.
And this without taking into account his career in the different leagues in which he has played.
Who was the best coach in Puerto Rico?
That is a difficult question.
We had a number of good coaches like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
I like the work of Leo Arill.
What do you think is the best thing you've achieved in the association?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN in the early 1990s up to 17 teams in a season.
What do you have to do?
There are things that I would have introduced, such as the regionalization of the lower categories.
That the guys in Ponce, for example, play only in their area and only in the national playoffs meet teams from other corners of the island.
Today, children make unnecessary many trips and games.
At least I see the result of the prescribed trainings and courses for coaches, table officials and referees.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I enjoy listening to music, watching videos of music from my time on YouTube, enjoying my grandchildren and occasionally going to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who has always been by my side.
